The polynomial \( p(x) \) is given to have degree 1008, so \( N = 1008 \). Thus, \( d = N - 1008 = 0 \). For the second problem, the conditions \( |f'(x)| \leq |g(x)| \) and \( |g'(x)| \leq |f(x)| \) imply \( |\theta'(x)| \leq 1 \), where \( \theta(x) \) is the angle in the representation \( (f(x), g(x)) = (|u(x)| \cos \theta(x), |u(x)| \sin \theta(x)) \). With \( f(0) > 0 \) and \( g(0) = 0 \), we have \( \theta(0) = 0 \). To achieve \( f(r) = 0 \), we need \( \theta(r) = \pi/2 \), requiring a rotation of \( \pi/2 \). Since \( |\theta'| \leq 1 \), the minimum time is \( r \geq \pi/2 \). The functions \( f(x) = \cos x \) and \( g(x) = \sin x \) satisfy all conditions with \( r = \pi/2 \), proving optimality.

